@{B}Legalese
********@{UB}

   As with any piece of commercial software, there are some rules that
need to be followed. They tell you what you may or may not do with Amiga
Envoy and you should be aware of them before trying to make use of
Amiga Envoy.

   Amiga Envoy 3.0 is copyrighted, commercial software. It is not
freely redistributable, shareware or in the public domain. You may
install it on to a permanent storage device, load it into temporary
memory, and copy it as required for reasonable backup purposes. You may
not otherwise copy it. You may not rent, lease, or sublicense the
product.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} One license of Amiga Envoy may be used for up to two Amiga
computers. If you have more Amiga computers that need to be connected,
you have to obtain one license for each pair of Amiga computers. If you
have, e.g., seven Amiga computers, you have 3.5 pairs. So you need to
obtain four licenses to connect all these computers.

   The product is provided @{B}as is@{UB} without warranty of any kind, either
expressed or implied, statuory or otherwise, including without
limitation any implied warranties of non-infringement, merchantibility
and fitness for a particular purpose. The entire risk as to use,
results and performance of the product is assumed by you and should the
product prove to be defective, you asume the entire cost of all
necessary servicing, repair or other remediation. In no event shall the
author be liable for any property damage, personal injury, loss of use
or other indirect, incidental or consequential damages, including
without limitation any damages for lost profits, business interruption
or data which may be lost or rendered inaccurate, even if we have been
advised of the possibility of such damages.

Thank you for reading this.


@EndNode


@Node "Introduction" "EnvoyManual.guide/Introduction"

@Next "Requirements"
@Prev "Legalese"
@Toc "Main"

@{B}Introduction
************@{UB}

   Welcome to Amiga Envoy.  Amiga Envoy is the only networking software
specifically designed for Amiga computers. It allows you to access
resources like files and directories on connected Amiga computers as if
they were on a local disk. Naturally, this also includes removable
media support.  Printing over the network is also a feature of Amiga
Envoy. A single printer can even be accessed by multiple Amiga computers
simultaneously.

   Via security and management features, you can also set up access
restrictions in a flexible way for multiple users.

   Amiga Envoy is easy to use and easy to configure with its font
sensitive graphical user interface. Contrary to common types of
networking software, there is no need to restart after changing any
configuration settings.

   The open programmer's interface of Amiga Envoy allows you to add
your own or freely redistributable extensions and services to, e.g.,
update date and time from a remote Amiga computer or even use a remote
Amiga computer with your local keyboard and screen. All the required
documentation is included.

   Amiga Envoy requires OS 2.04 or higher, at least 1MB of memory, and
any SANA-II compliant networking hardware. A harddisk is recommended.

Happy networking!

   Heinz Wrobel


@EndNode


@Node "Requirements" "EnvoyManual.guide/Requirements"

@Next "Beginner's Info"
@Prev "Introduction"
@Toc "Main"

@{B}Requirements for using Amiga Envoy 3.0
**************************************@{UB}

   To connect your Amiga computers, you need to have some kind of
physical network between them. Amiga Envoy relies on the existence of
well working networking hardware with an AmigaOS device compatible to
SANA-II, the standard Amiga networking architecture.  Please install
your networking hardware and the device needed before installing Amiga
Envoy. We recommend Ethernet or ARCNET hardware, if possible, as this
is commonly the fastest and most convenient way to set up a network
with Amiga computers.

   Amiga Envoy is for @{B}networking@{UB} Amiga computers. So while you can use
it on a single Amiga computer, commonly it is used when you have more
than one Amiga computer. Please check @{"Legalese" Link "Legalese"} to determine how many
licenses of Amiga Envoy you need to buy for your network. To sum it up,
you need one license for each pair of Amiga computers that you have on
your network.

   At least one of the Amiga computers you are using should have a hard
disk with at least 500KB free in your system drive `SYS:' and at least
2MB free space for Amiga Envoy anywhere else on that hard disk.

   An OS version of at least V37 (i.e. Kickstart and Workbench 2.04) is
required. OS 3.1 (V40) is recommended. You won't get far if you don't
have at least 512KB free RAM space. More free memory is preferred.
Amiga Envoy will run happily with a plain 8 MHz 68000 CPU, but a faster
processor is preferred.


@EndNode


