@{B}Beginner's Info
***************@{UB}

   You have decided to network your Amiga computers, but you don't
really know yet what you are getting into, right? This chapter of the
manual will explain a few basic concepts of networking, as far as Amiga
Envoy is concerned. Reading through it should take you about five
minutes at most. Some abbreviations will be thrown in.  If I don't
explain them, just take them as they are because every knowledgable
person will know what you are talking about. You don't really always
need to know everything at once. If in doubt, just come back to this
chapter and reread parts of it.


 @{" Concepts " Link "Concepts"}                 Basic networking concepts
 @{" Hardware and Cables " Link "Hardware and Cables"}      The hardware you need
 @{" The Hardware's Software " Link "The Hardware's Software"}  The software you need for the hardware
 @{" Addresses and IP " Link "Addresses and IP"}         Identifying Amiga computers in the net
 @{" Envoy Terminology " Link "Envoy Terminology"}        All those strange special terms


@EndNode


@Node "Concepts" "EnvoyManual.guide/Concepts"

@Next "Hardware and Cables"
@Prev "Beginner's Info"
@Toc "Beginner's Info"

@{B}Some Basic Networking Concepts
==============================@{UB}

@{B}Protocol Stacks
---------------@{UB}

   Amiga Envoy is for "networking" Amiga computers. Basically this
implies that more than one Amiga computer are somehow physically
connected to exchange all kinds of information. On existing networking
hardware, Amiga Envoy can handle the software side of connecting your
Amiga computers. This software side is called a "protocol stack",
meaning that Amiga Envoy has software inside that implements some
communication protocols for connecting Amiga computers. Without the
correct protocols to be followed on either side of a connection in the
correct order, the computers would not understand each other.

   Different types of protocol stacks are used for different purposes.
Amiga Envoy is used especially for connecting Amiga computers.  A
protocol stack implementing the TCP/IP suite of communication protocols
is geared towards connecting your computer to the Internet.

@{B}Network Types
-------------@{UB}

   Networking can be a lot of things. It can refer to just an Amiga
computer sitting on your desktop and one in the room next door.  This
would be a very small Local Area Network (a "LAN").  Networking can
also mean a Wide Area Network (a "WAN") possible spanning multiple
countries. It may also refer to a dial-up situation via a Modem to
connect to a LAN or WAN.

   A network built of computers hooked up to different cabling that is
interconnected is in many ways like a town built of houses on streets
interconnected via intersections with trafffic lights.

   Any type of network is usually built from connecting physical
"subnets" in some way. A phyical subnet consists of computers hooked up
to a single physical connection that can talk to each other without
needing additional help from outside the subnet. It's just like all the
houses on a single street. A few computers hooked up to a single
coaxial Ethernet cable would be a good example for a physical subnet.

   There is also the concept of a "logical subnet". A logical subnet
refers to the way addresses are used for the computers on a subnet. It
can either be the same as the physical subnet or split up one physical
subnet into multiple logical subnets by using differing addresses for
each one of them within the same physical subnet.

   Usually, you don't want to force a distinction between physical and
logical subnets.

   Subnets often help in logically structuring your network. You could
have an accounting subnet and an engineering subnet which are self
sufficient but can exchange data via some connection between them.

   To connect multiple subnets, a computer or special hardware is used
in a "gateway" or "bridging" function. It knows which data should go
across to the other side and only forwards data as needed. Compared to
dealing with a single subnet, this is a complex matter though.

@{B}Simple and Complex Networks
---------------------------@{UB}

   You can either have a "simple network", which means in Amiga Envoy
terminology that all computers are hooked up to a single physical
subnet. You can also have a "complex network". In a complex network,
you have multiple interconnected subnets or dial-up connections or
other magical extensions to a basic and simple subnet. Amiga computers
connecting to two or more of the different subnets at the same time
should act as gateway here.  Setting this up is somewhat complex, as
the name suggests.

@{B}Which network type is best for Amiga Envoy?
-------------------------------------------@{UB}

   Amiga Envoy is best used in a simple network situation with all
Amiga computers on the same subnet without any dial-up users. Amiga
Envoy should work well with multiple physical subnets, but this means
significantly more setup and configuration work, so it is not
recommended for a beginner. Amiga Envoy may work well in a WAN
situation or over dial-up lines, but it has not been tested in these
setups.


@EndNode


@Node "Hardware and Cables" "EnvoyManual.guide/Hardware and Cables"

@Next "The Hardware's Software"
@Prev "Concepts"
@Toc "Beginner's Info"

@{B}Hardware and Cables
===================@{UB}

   As two way radio connections are not that common in the Amiga world,
the "networking hardware" used is typically a physical connection,
e.g., two boards or hardware modules and some amount of special cabling
for two computers.

   Recommended types of networking hardware and cabling are Ethernet or
ARCNET due to the high data transfer speeds. Amiga Envoy will work with
other hardware, too, as long as it conforms to the SANA-II standard,
which is explained in @{"The Hardware's Software" Link "The Hardware's Software"}.

   Ethernet is normally set up with one of two types of cabling,
depending on the connectors your hardware has. I can recommend "RJ-45",
also called "twisted pair" cabling, because it is the most robust cable
setup at home and reasonably cheap. The RJ-45 plugs look a lot like
"western" or "ISDN" phone cable plugs. Usually, this type of cabling is
used together with a "hub" which acts as the central connection point
for the connected computers. The other type of cabling that is often
found is "RG-58 coaxial cable" that is connected to BNC connectors on
your board via special "T-Plugs" and 50 Ohm "terminator plugs" at each
cable end.

   ARCNET uses RG-62 coaxial cable, T-plugs, and terminator plugs.
Note that they look almost the same as the cabling for Ethernet but
have different electrical properties. Make sure that you you don't
accidently try to use Ethernet cabling for ARCNET or vice versa!  On
other thing is special about ARCNET. ARCNET boards usually have some
kind of DIP-switch or set of jumpers to give each board a unique
address. Always make sure that each board has a unique address setting.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} It is @{B}extremely important@{UB} to have all cabling set up correctly.
Please refer to the documentation of your networking hardware for more
information on how to set up the cables.


@EndNode


@Node "The Hardware's Software" "EnvoyManual.guide/The Hardware's Software"

@Next "Addresses and IP"
@Prev "Hardware and Cables"
@Toc "Beginner's Info"

@{B}The Hardware's Software
=======================@{UB}

   The networking hardware alone won't get you anywhere because Amiga
Envoy needs to know which hardware you have and a way to use it.  For
this, each piece of networking hardware comes with an AmigaOS "device",
also often called "driver", which is a piece of software that acts as
interface from the hardware to Amiga Envoy or other protocol stacks.
Make sure that the device is compliant to the Standard Amiga Networking
Architecture Version 2 "SANA-II", as this is what Amiga Envoy knows how
to use. If your networking hardware has a device that is compliant to
Release 2 of SANA-II, which is often written as SANA-IIR2, you can use
multiple protocol stacks at the same time on the same networking
hardware. You can run, e.g., Amiga Envoy and a TCP/IP protocol stack on
the same Ethernet card with a Release 2 compliant device.


@EndNode


@Node "Addresses and IP" "EnvoyManual.guide/Addresses and IP"

@Next "Envoy Terminology"
@Prev "The Hardware's Software"
@Toc "Beginner's Info"

@{B}Addresses and IP
================@{UB}

   You have read a lot about hardware and devices now, but one
important point has been neglected. How do you identify a computer on
the net? Numbers play a big role in networking anyway and numbers are
used to identify just about anything because they can easily be made
unique. Each computer needs to get a unique address to be reached, much
like your post office needs to know your unique address and ZIP code to
get mail to you.

   This is where "IP", the Internet Protocol, helps us. Amiga Envoy is
built upon IP internally, which defines a way to send data packets
between computers using a certain addressing scheme. Each computer is
identified via an address consisting of four decimal values in the
range of 0 to 255 separated by a dot. Here are some examples for
addresses:

     192.0.0.1
     198.14.3.2
     163.1.2.254

   The catch here is that not every single combination is a valid or
permissible one. The rules are described well in various standards
documents, but you probably don't want to read somewhat cryptic
standards. This summary of how to select an address for your Amiga
computer works well for the typical user:

   À If you are connected to a company network, ask your local network
     administrator about IP address values for each Amiga computer. @{B}Do
     not@{UB} try to chose any one yourself.

   À If you are in a complex network situation (See the description in
     @{"Concepts" Link "Concepts"}), you should ask the network administrator. If you are
     the administrator and don't know about IP addresses, you should
     read, e.g., "Internetworking with TCP/IP" by Douglas E. Comer.

   À If you are connected to an outside network in some way do the
     same.

   À If you only connect less than 255 Amiga computers locally, follow
     the steps below.

   À The first three values should be 192.168.0, which are safe
     defaults for a local net.

   À Set the last value to any value from 1 to 254. Do not use 0 or
     255, as these values have a special meaning.

   By using 192.168.0.x addressing as described above, you can connect
up to 254 computers on a single net. If you have more than that or if
you have multiple physical nets hooked together somehow, you should
think hard about buying an introductory textbook about IP network setup
and management.

   There is one more thing worth mentioning here. Any Amiga computer on
the net needs a way to find the adresses of other computers on the same
net. For this, the Address Resolution Protocol "ARP" is used. Without
ARP you would have to tell each computer about all the addresses of all
the other computers on the same net. This can easily become very
tedious. If your networking hardware supports ARP and if Amiga Envoy is
configured to use ARP, you don't have to worry about all this.


@EndNode


@Node "Envoy Terminology" "EnvoyManual.guide/Envoy Terminology"

@Prev "Addresses and IP"
@Toc "Beginner's Info"

@{B}Amiga Envoy Terminology
=======================@{UB}

   Many concepts in Amiga Envoy have special names. This is a list of
the most common terms:

   À "Host" Any Amiga computer that you can use or access on your
     Amiga Envoy network is called a host.

   À "Server"

     An Amiga computer that is configured to make some of its resources
     (e.g., files or printers) available on the net.

   À "Exports"

     The process of configuring any resources to be available on the net
     on a server is called exporting those resources. The resources
     themselves can then be simply called "exports".

   À "Service"

     The piece of software that actually makes configured exports
     available on the net is called a service. Via, e.g., the
     `printspool.service', you make printers of a server actually
     available on the net. A service can make other kinds of
     functionality available, too, like the current date and time.

   À "Client"

     An Amiga computer or piece of software running on it that uses
     resources on a Server by connecting to it and exchanging data.

   À "Imports"

     The process of connecting to a server and some exported resource on
     it is called importing that resource. The resource itself can then
     be simply called "Import".

   À "Security"

     The Amiga is really not a computer system built for security. So
     Amiga Envoy security features are more like safety features. They
     help you protect yourself and your network from accidental misuse
     of resources. They are not designed to withstand malicious attacks
     on your network.

   À "EFS"

     An abbreviation for Envoy File System. This is the networking
     filesystem that allows you to share files and directories with
     other Amiga computers. There is an EFS Server to handle exports
     and an EFS Client to handle imports.

   À "EPS"

     An abbreviation for the Envoy Print Spooler. In the context of
     Amiga Envoy, it does not refer to Encapsulated PostScript.  The
     EPS Server is the print spooler which handles your print jobs.
     The EPS Client is what sends data from `printer.device' to the
     print spooler.


@EndNode


@Node "Major Changes" "EnvoyManual.guide/Major Changes"

@Next "Installation"
@Prev "Beginner's Info"
@Toc "Main"

@{B}Major Changes
*************@{UB}

   Most likely you are interested in what has been changed in Amiga
Envoy 3.0 compared to previous versions of Envoy. Well, the actual list
of changes is fairly long and can be found in the file `FixedBugs',
which is part of the Amiga Envoy distribution. Not all changes are just
bug fixes, so this file should really be named `Release Notes', but is
not for historical reasons. Over 2000 lines of changes and enhancements
are documented in that file. A much shorter and somewhat simplified
summary is this:

   À @{B}Amiga Envoy 3.0 is incompatible to previous versions of Envoy. Do
     not use it in mixed setups.@{UB}

   À Much faster transfer speeds.

   À Font sensitive Graphical User Interface

   À On-Line Help with AmigaOS 3.1

   À Extended documentation

   À Complete Reconfiguration without reboot.

   À All new network printing support with timeout checks and
     diagnostics.

   À Fully IP based according to RFCs.

   À New security and management features.

   À Supports a variety of underlying network hardware

   À Built in diagnostic support.


@EndNode


@Node "Installation" "EnvoyManual.guide/Installation"

@Next "Configuration"
@Prev "Major Changes"
@Toc "Main"

@{B}Installation
************@{UB}

   The installation assumes a reasonable amount of knowledge about your
Amiga computer. If you don't know what disks, volumes, files or
directories are, if you don't know how to use or handle them, or if you
are not comfortable using either Workbench or a Shell, you should refer
to the User's Manuals of your Amiga computer first.

To install Amiga Envoy 3.0, follow these steps:

  1. If in doubt about what to enter, always chose the suggested
     default value.

  2. Install your networking hardware while your Amiga computers are
     powered off. Make sure to read the documentation that accompanies
     whatever networking hardware you have.

  3. Make sure that the SANA-II device for your networking hardware is
     correctly installed in `DEVS:Networks'.

  4. Run any test that the hardware manufacturer has supplied with your
     networking hardware to make sure that it is working well.  Do not
     try to install Amiga Envoy if there is any indication that the
     networking hardware is not working well.

  5. Double click on the Installation Icon to install Amiga Envoy.

  6. Follow the suggested steps carefully.

  7. Continue with the @{"Configuration" Link "Configuration"}.



@EndNode


