@{B}Important Configuration Information
===================================@{UB}

   After an update or installation you want to configure Amiga Envoy to
do what you want it to do for you. This includes, but is not limited
to, the login information (user names and passwords), a configuration
of the basic networking hardware, and the filesystems and printers to
export and import.

   You must decide on a name and number for each Amiga.  The name will
be used by people to refer to that Amiga, so it should be easy to
remember and to type. Have fun by choosing a common theme for all your
names: comic strip characters, elements, fruits, liquors, etc.  The
numbers, on the other hand, will only be used by the computers, not by
humans. For simple networks, each network number must be a unique
integer between 1 and 254. Simply start counting from the first name
you assign to the last. That way you won't have any duplicates.
Remember that you need to purchase one copy of the Amiga Envoy package
for each two machines being used on your network.

   You should also decide which Amigas will export files or printers to
other Amigas. Typically, most Amigas with a hard disk and/or CD-ROM
drive will export files. Most Amigas with a printer will export that
printer if some Amigas are printerless.

   Get a piece of paper. Write a name and number for each Amiga you are
going to network. For each Amiga, write down which volumes or
directories, if any, will be exported. Make a name for each of these
exports (what the filesystem will be called on any clients) and write
that down. Write down whether the Amiga will export a printer. If an
Amiga will be importing a printer and/or any filesystem(s), make a note
of that. Optionally, quickly sketch a diagram of how your Amigas are
physically located and connected.  Even with the smallest networks,
this planning will make installation easier.

   After a fresh installation or an update of Amiga Envoy most of the
configuration information will already be set. In fact, often you may
not have to change a thing, except for setting up imports and exports
that you want. It still is always a good idea to look at the
configuration once after an installation or update of Amiga Envoy to
check that things are in order.

   Each description of an Amiga Envoy preferences editor will start out
with some comments and a little tutorial. You may want to go through
this before you check out the annotated list of special menu functions
or gadgets that follows.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} that with OS 3.0 and better, you can press the `HELP' key over
gadgets to get additional help on functions.  This manual concentrates
on tutorial information.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} You have to check or configure the login information before you
can configure the rest of Amiga Envoy after a fresh installation.


@EndNode


@Node "Login Information" "EnvoyManual.guide/Login Information"

@Next "Users"
@Prev "ConfigFirst"
@Toc "Configuration"

@{B}Login Information
=================@{UB}

   This section should tell you all you need to know about logins,
passwords, security issues and other related issues. It also mentions
the initial user name and password that you get after a new
installation of Amiga Envoy. @{B}Read all this at least once very carefully!@{UB}

@{B}Security and False Assumptions
------------------------------@{UB}

   Amiga Envoy features quite a few so called security features.
Maintenance and configuration functions are protected by user name and
password combinations. You can also set up groups of user accounts who
are allowed to do similar things. The same type of protection can be
used for files imported via the Amiga Envoy filesystem, remote printing
or other Amiga Envoy based services.

   This helps you protect your network from accidental misuse of
resources, makes it easier to structure legitimate access to resources,
and sometimes simply keeps you from doing something stupid with your
files if you protected them from inadvertent accesses.

   While the builtin security features are set up well for casual users
of a network, they are not and cannot be secure enough to withstand a
malicious attack. The Amiga is an inherently insecure computer system.
It is possible for a knowledgable bad guy to install software that
snoops your password or circumvents the security features of Amiga
Envoy in some other way.

   It is therefore wise, as with most other computer systems, not to
rely solely on built in security features. Security is a lot more like
a safety feature in Amiga Envoy. It can try to catch accidental misuse
or intentional abuse, but it can't really make your Amiga network fully
secure.

   Let me list a few legitimate uses of the security features:

   À Protect finished software from accidental overwrite

   À Keep simpleminded B. J. User from wasting expensive slides on the
     color laserprinter that he should not be able to access via the
     network.

   À Make certain files readable by everyone but writable only for a
     few selected persons.

@{B}Users, Groups, and Passwords
----------------------------@{UB}

   Users of your network can have different user names to identify
themselves to Amiga Envoy. For each user you can optionally define a
password to reduce the chances that someone simply abuses someone
else's user name. Obviously some users must be able to adminstrate
other user's login information. Naturally, these users are called
administrators or Admins and have special privileges to do exactly that.

   You can establish groups of users to make, e.g., files accessible to
a whole group at once and not just a single user.

@{B}Initial Login Configuration
---------------------------@{UB}

   After you have set up a fresh installation of Amiga Envoy, only one
user entry will have been established. The username is `Admin' and the
password is also `Admin'. This is the user account that is set up to
let you modify any part of the configuration settings of Amiga Envoy.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} You don't have to protect everything with security features. It
is an option that may help you, but you don't have to use it. Only an
admin user has to be configured at all times and for configuration
changes, you have to log in as an admin user.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} User names or group names are not case sensitive.  @{B}Passwords are
case sensitive.@{UB} If you don't type passwords exactly as they should be,
they won't be accepted. User names and passwords are treated as a
unity. If you don't enter correct information for both of them, if
required, the typed in username will be rejected as non existent.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} It is wise to change the password of the Admin user to a very
private one right after the installation. If you want to know how to
change a password, you should read the section about the @{"Users" Link "Users"}
preferences editor.


@EndNode


@Node "Users" "EnvoyManual.guide/Users"

@Next "Groups"
@Prev "Login Information"
@Toc "Configuration"

@{B}Users
=====@{UB}

   When you start the Users preferences editor, you are asked to
identify yourself to Amiga Envoy. If this is the very first time that
you have to do this, you should read the section @{"Login Information" Link "Login Information"}
first.

   If you don't want to make use of the security features, you probably
only want to set up admin users or passwords to protect your
configuration from arbitrary or accidental changes due to an incorrect
privilege level for a normal user.

@{B}Tutorial
--------@{UB}

   You have logged in with admin privileges, right? If not, please read
the section @{"Login Information" Link "Login Information"} now!

  1. You want to create another admin user BillAdmin, a normal user
     JoeNormal, and a user needing a password called JimSafe.

  2. Click on `Create' now to set up a new user and change the name to
     BillAdmin. Don't forget to hit `ENTER' after entering the name to
     actually change it!

  3. Right now, BillAdmin doesn't have any privileges. Just check
     `Administrator Privileges' to give him the right to do everything
     that is called `May do something' for himself and anyone else.

  4. It is unwise to leave an administrator without a password, so
     check `Requires Password' and set a password by clicking `Select
     Password...'. @{B}Never@{UB} use simple passwords like birthdates or the
     name of your cat. @{B}Always@{UB} use really cryptic and meaningless
     combinations like `sl12fn8i', which is a good combination to enter
     in this tutorial @{B}only@{UB}.

  5. Click on `Create' to set up another new user and change the name
     to JoeNormal. As JoeNormal is only allowed to do what the admin
     has set up for him to use, he doesn't get any special privileges.

  6. Click on `Create' to set up another new user and change the name
     to JimSafe. As this user is paranoid and always wants a relatively
     secure password, check `Requires Password'. You can also trust
     this user to manage his own password, so check `May change
     password'. Finally, give this guy some password of at least six
     characters.

  7. Use the `New Login' function in the `Settings' menu now to log in
     as BillAdmin, JoeNormal, and JimSafe. Check that the different
     users have different privileges. The admin can do everything,
     JoeNormal can't do anything, and JimSafe can at least change his
     own password.

  8. We are about done. Login as admin user again and remove our three
     tutorial users if you don't want to do more tutorials. If you do,
     keep the three users for now, but don't forget to delete them
     eventually!

  9. You may have noticed that there are no `Save', `Use', or `Cancel'
     buttons. Within the Users and Groups preferences editors, all
     changes are immediate!


@{B}Gadgets and Menus
-----------------@{UB}

   Below is a description of all the gadgets and non-standard menus in
this preferences editor.

The non-standard menu entries:

   À Settings/Select Host

     If you use this option, you can connect to an arbitrary host in
     your network for configuring users. Basically this means, that each
     host in your network could potentially have a totally different
     user database unless you take care to enter the same information
     into all of them. If you want to use only a single user database on
     only a single computer, you should read the advanced topic
     @{"Accounts Server Sharing" Link "Accounts Server Sharing"}.

   À Settings/New Login

     Different users have different privileges. You may have logged in
     as a normal user just to change your password and now you have,
     e.g., decided that new users need to be created. With this menu
     function, you can change your current login setting to any other
     user. For creating new users you would have to log in with
     administration privileges.

   Below is a list of the gadgets that you can use in this preferences
editor. Some gadgets may only be enabled if your access privileges are
sufficient.

   À `Available Users' Listview

     The listview gadget shows you all the available users.  With the
     string gadget and the buttons below the list view you can change
     user names by entering a new one and pressing `ENTER'. You can
     also  add or delete users, depending on your access privileges. By
     clicking on a user you select the user specific settings for
     possible modification.

   À `Select Password...' Button

     If you want to change the password for the currently selected user,
     you can click on this gadget. An admin user may change any
     password.

   À `Select Group...' Button

     Any user may optionally belong to a definable group of users. Read
     section @{"Groups" Link "Groups"} to see how groups are defined.

   À `Primary Group:' Text display

     This gadget shows the currently selected group for this user.

   À `Administrator Privileges:' Checkmark

     Use this to enable full administrator privileges for this user. You
     should activate the `Requires Password' Checkmark for any admin
     user, too, which is not automatically included in the general
     admin features!

   À `May create groups:' Checkmark

     Even though a user may not be granted full admin rights, he or she
     may be allowed to set up groups of other users for further
     configurations. This checkmark enables that feature.

   À `May change name:' Checkmark

     Typically, a user name remains always the same. Sometimes, a user
     may be allowed to change her user name anyway. This can be useful
     for testing purposes, but is usually not used in general.

   À `May change password:' Checkmark

     Typically, an admin wants any user to be able to change his
     password by himself. Use this checkmark to enable this feature.

   À `Requires password:' Checkmark

     Unless you activate this checkmark, passwords don't play a big
     role. As soon as you set this checkmark, the respective user is
     required to enter his correct password for a successful login.
     You most likely want to activate this gadget for all admin users!

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} You can never delete the original Admin user. You can rename it,
but never delete it. This is to protect yourself from accidents.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} Never forget that passwords have to be entered case sensitive.
Uppercase letters and lowercase letters are different!


@EndNode


@Node "Groups" "EnvoyManual.guide/Groups"

@Next "Network Configuration"
@Prev "Users"
@Toc "Configuration"

@{B}Groups
======@{UB}

   When you start the Groups preferences editor, you are asked to
identify yourself to Amiga Envoy. If this is the very first time that
you have to do this, you should read the section @{"Login Information" Link "Login Information"}
first.

   If you don't want to make use of the security features, you really
don't have to deal with the Groups preferences editor at all.

   With groups of users, it is often easier to set up access rights
than for individual users. Assume that you have a public relations
department and an engineering department. The guys from engineering,
whoever they are, should not be able to access the special color
laserprinter from the PR department. The easy way to enforce this is to
set up a group naed `PR' and allow access to that printer only for
members of that group, not for individuals. That way, you don'thave to
reconfigure everything just because someone got hired or fired in the
PR department. You just change group membership.

   For a very simple network, you may not really want to deal with
groups at all. Again, it's just an option, not a requirement.

@{B}Tutorial
--------@{UB}

   You have logged in with admin privileges, right? If not, please read
the section @{"Login Information" Link "Login Information"} now!

  1. You still have our three tutorial users BillAdmin, JoeNormal, and
     JimSafe set up from the Users tutorial? If not, please check
     section @{"Users" Link "Users"} and set them up again.

  2. Log in as admin user. You can either use your original Admin
     account or BillAdmin.

  3. JoeNormal and JimSafe both work in the accounting department.
     They have a special printer with special paper that may only be
     used by accountants So you want to set up a group for the
     accountants. This group name can then be used to control printer
     access.

  4. Click on the `Create' button to create a new group. Then change
     the name from `NewGroup' to `Accounting' in the string gadget and
     don't forget to press `ENTER'.

  5. The group has been created, but you don't have any members yet.
     Select the group by clicking in the listview on the group's name.

  6. You can now select group members by clicking on the `Add...'
     button. Add both JoeNormal and JimSafe.


@{B}NOTE:@{UB} You can use group names when setting up filesystem or printer
exports to allow access for multiple users belonging to a single group.
Simply add the group name to the respective access list rather than all
the user names.


@EndNode


@Node "Network Configuration" "EnvoyManual.guide/Network Configuration"

@Next "Services Configuration"
@Prev "Groups"
@Toc "Configuration"

@{B}Network Configuration
=====================@{UB}

   The Network Configuration preferences editor is most likely the most
complex part of the Amiga Envoy configuration tool set. Don't despair.
The installation has typically set up everything you need here, so the
tutorial will be more of a descriptive walk through that includes the
gadget descriptions.

   You are not required to know all this information but it never hurts
to know what is going on inside the computer, right?

@{B}Tutorial
--------@{UB}

   You have logged into Network Configuration with admin privileges,
right? If not, please read the section @{"Login Information" Link "Login Information"} now!

   À Log in as admin user. If you don't have admin privileges, Network
     Configuration will refuse to open.

   À The Host Configuration Page

     You see the configuration page now. Later, you can use the cycle
     gadget in the upper left to see what other pages exist. For now,
     just read on, and use the cycle gadget to advance to the next
     option page, when you reach the corresponding description in this
     text.

        - Basic information like the name of this Amiga computer or the
          owner's name can be set here. Note that each computer name
          should be unique. You should never have two computers with
          exactly the same name on the same network.

        - On the right, you have two settings for complex networks. If
          your Amiga computer is hooked up to more than one physical
          network at the same time, and if you want it to act as
          gateway between the networks, enable gateway functionality.
          Don't do this if it isn't needed.

        - The other setting is used when you set up realms, a feature
          of complex networks. Please read the chapter
          @{"Complex Networks and Realms" Link "Complex Networks and Realms"} for more information before
          you start playing with this checkmark.

   À The Device Configuration Page

     If you set up Envoy for the first time or if you have problems
     connecting to other Amiga computers, you want to check this page.
     You can find all the SANA-II device interface configurations for
     Envoy here and check, add, remove, or modify them, depending on
     what kind of networking hardware you have. Envoy relies on this
     information to be correct.

        - The list view on the left lists all the currently configured
          network interfaces. You can give a descriptive name to each
          one of them. You may want to name your Ethernet device `eth0'
          or your ARCNET device `arcnet0'. Descriptive names are always
          useful.  if the list is empty, you should configure an
          interface because Envoy can't connect to the outside world
          without an interface description.

        - Each interface has multiple settings. Select an interface in
          the list view and you see how the display of all the setting
          in the right half of the window changes.

        - `IP-Address:'

          This is the unique address for this Amiga computer. You have
          read @{"Addresses and IP" Link "Addresses and IP"}, right?

        - `Subnet Mask:'

          If you are into complex networking, you may want to specify a
          subnet mask here. For simple networksm, leave this set to
          default values.

        - `Address:'

          This is for very strange networking hardware. Aside from the
          IP address, each piece of hardware tends to have a unique
          hardware address. Some networking hardware doesn't know about
          its own address. With this gadget you can define a specific
          hardware address to be used for this interface by writing a
          suitable hex number into the gadget without any separator
          characters. If you haven't a clue what this is all about,
          leave it set to default values.

        - `IP Type:' and `ARP Type:'

          Usually, you just leave this set to default values. If you
          are also using a TCP/IP protocol stack, you may want to refer
          to @{"TCP and Amiga Envoy" Link "TCP and Amiga Envoy"}.

        - `Device:' and `Unit:'

          This specifies which SANA-II device is to be used for this
          interface. By clicking on the selection gadget to the right,
          you can chose the correct device from a file requester.
          Typically, SANA-II devices are stored in `DEVS:Networks' on
          you Amiga computer. Set the unit corresponding to the
          documentation that came with your networking hardware and the
          SANA-II device.  Often, but not always is 0 the correct unit
          setting!

        - `Device is active:'

          This tells Envoy to use the configured interface or not. Envoy
          will use it only if you have marked it as active. If you
          forget to mark it as active, Envoy will ignore it completely.
          This also means that you don't have to fully remove an
          interface configuration if you just want to stop using it.

        - `Use packet filtering:'

          Typically, you want to have this setting turned off. For some
          SANA-II devices, it may result in a slight speed increase, but
          typically it really doesn't.

   À The Gateway Configuration page

     This page is used only in complex networks to configure static
     routes to certain gateways or hosts, including a default gateway.
     If you don't know what this is about, you don't have to deal with
     it at all. Just leave it empty. You enter destination net or host
     IP addresses and corresponding gateway IP addresses here.

   À The Realm Configuration page

     This page will only appear, if you have configured this Amiga
     computer to act as realm server in the Host Configuration Page. If
     you got here, you most likely have a complex network setup and you
     know what you are doing right? If not, you may want to read
     @{"Complex Networks and Realms" Link "Complex Networks and Realms"}.


@EndNode


@Node "Services Configuration" "EnvoyManual.guide/Services Configuration"

@Next "Filesystem Exports"
@Prev "Network Configuration"
@Toc "Configuration"

@{B}Services Configuration
======================@{UB}

   Envoy offers you different services, like filesystem or printer
exports. With this preferences editor, you can configure the services
that should be active on this Amiga computer and you can activate or
deactivate them if needed. Only a few things need to be said about this
as the standard services are preconfigured.

  1. You have to log in with admin privileges to do anything with
     Services Configuration.

  2. If you can't use a certain service that should really be available
     already, make sure it is both added here and marked as active.

  3. When adding a new service, you will see a file requester which
     allows you to select the service to add.

  4. Removing a service does not delete it on disk. It just removes the
     configuration entry.


@{B}NOTE:@{UB} The service is used via it's full file path. If you move service
files on you hard disk, you may have to remove and re-add them here to
get the path that is expected.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} Deactivating a service just stops new requests to use it. Every
client who is already using that service will be able to continue using
it until it disconnects from that service.


@EndNode


@Node "Filesystem Exports" "EnvoyManual.guide/Filesystem Exports"

@Next "Filesystem Imports"
@Prev "Services Configuration"
@Toc "Configuration"

@{B}Filesystem Exports
==================@{UB}

   To make files and directories available to other Amiga computers on
the Envoy network, you use Filesystem Exports. At allows you to set up
arbitrary number of exports with a descriptive name and optional
security and access options each.

@{B}Tutorial
--------@{UB}

   The idea of this tutorial is to create an export of your boot volume
`SYS:' and to point out a few implications of some of the different
options.

  1. You have to log in with admin privileges to do anything with
     Filesystem Exports. If you don't know how, you may want to back up
     to @{"Login Information" Link "Login Information"}.

  2. If you click on `Add...', a file requester appears that allows you
     to either select or type in an arbitrary disk or directory name.
     You can also type in the name of a physical DOS device like
     `DF0:'. Use `SYS:' for now.

  3. A new export named `Export_0' has been created for you.  Well, if
     you have created other exports before, the number may be different.

  4. Change the name to `FirstExport'. Don't forget to hit `ENTER' to
     cause the name change.

  5. In the path gadget, you see `SYS:' from the file requester. You
     could change this to any other location described by a DOS path.
     For now, leave it as is.

  6. Please look at the checkmarks now. Your workbench is a volume, not
     some DOS device where you can insert removable media.  So please
     remove the removable media checkmark.

  7. For this test, this is going to be a fairly public, but totally
     read only export. Please check `Read only' to make sure that no
     client can modify your data.

  8. Click on the cycle gadget now to switch to the security page.  You
     may notice that security is turned on for export mounts and
     individual files. We want to let anyone import this and we want
     anyone to be able to read access all the files. So click on the
     security cycle gadget once to turn off special security checks.

  9. Now click on `Use' and anyone on the network will immediately be
     able to import your Workbench. Check @{"Filesystem Imports" Link "Filesystem Imports"} for more
     information. If you want this test export to survive reboots of
     this Amiga computer, you should click on `Save' instead.


@{B}Gadgets
-------@{UB}

   À The list view

     You can see all the exports with their respective descriptive names
     in the list view. You can also change the names by selecting an
     export and typing in a new name for it. Don't forget to hit
     `ENTER' to cause the name change.

   À The Standard Option page

        - `Path:'

          This is the actual DOS path that is exported. The client will
          never see it. You can specify any valid DOS path here,
          referring to disk devices, volumes, or directories.

        - `Removable Medium:'

          It is impossible for Envoy to determine if you exports refers
          to a disk device that supports removable media like `DF0:' or
          to a hard disk, which is fixed. You have to help here by
          specifying which kind of export this is. For removable media,
          the client will always see the true volume name of whatever
          is inserted. For fixed media, you configured descriptive name
          will be used as volume name and disk changes will not be
          handled.

        - `Allow Volume snapshotting:'

          If you export a volume, it is normally not wise to let the
          client snapshot your volume icon in whatever position it is
          on the client's Workbench because it messes up the looks on
          your Workbench. So you have the choice to enable write access
          to the volume's `Disk.info' file for any clients here.

        - `Allow left-out icons:'

          The same thing as for volume snapshots is true for left out
          icons.  If you have many left out icons on an exported
          volume, you often don't want them to appear on the client.
          Using this option, you can disable any access to a Workbench
          `.backdrop' file to stop client from having to deal with left
          out icons.

        - `Emulate ExAll():'

          Some filesystems have problems handling the DOS function
          `ExAll()' correctly. Envoy knows about the FastFileSystem but
          not about any filesystem that may be out there. If you have
          serious problems listing files on an export from a client
          correctly, try to set this checkmark. If this helps, contact
          the vendor of your filesystem and ask about a bug fix.

        - `Read Only:'

          Rather than specifying access restrictions for every single
          file and directory, it is sometimes handy to have something
          exported as read only, independent of what the true access
          permissions of files and directories are. With this
          checkmark, you set a general write protection for an export.

   À The Security Option page

     If you want to establish access restrictions for individual users
     or groups on individual files, directories, you need to deal with
     this option page.

        - `Security:'

          This cycle gadget controls the security features. If you turn
          off all security checks, anyone can mount or access the files
          of the selected export. By specifying `Mounts' here, only the
          listed users or groups of users may actually successfully
          import this export. File access is not restricted. Full
          security can be set up with the `Mounts&Files' setting. In
          addition to the mount restrictions, all file accesses are
          verified against the access information for each file that is
          handled by the underlying file system.

        - `Users and Groups'

          You specify in this list view all the users and groups who may
          mount this export. This check is only done if security is not
          turned off.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} It is normally unwise to export `RAM:' because this is where the
general Amiga configuration information is stored in `ENV:'. If you
allow other people access to this information, they may either modify
it or maybe read private configuration settings that they should not be
able to access.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} Changing any options for an export will only be applicable to new
imports done by a client. Exports that are currently mounted by clients
will remain as they are. The option change will only take effect if the
client loses and reestablishes contact to these exports.


@EndNode


@Node "Filesystem Imports" "EnvoyManual.guide/Filesystem Imports"

@Next "Printer Exports"
@Prev "Filesystem Exports"
@Toc "Configuration"

@{B}Filesystem Imports
==================@{UB}

   Filesystem Imports is used to mount exports that were configured on
this or any other Amiga computer running Amiga Envoy. You can specify
temporary mounts, have them stored, or have them set up permanently
across reboots of your client.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} You may want to run a client without having to bother with any
security features. If you enable the Workbench tooltype `NOSECURITY'
for Filesystem Imports, you won't be asked for your user name and
password on startup. Obviously this also means that you can only access
exports that are not protected by security features then.

@{B}Tutorial
--------@{UB}

   You will import the export `FirstExport' that you created in
@{"Filesystem Exports" Link "Filesystem Exports"}.

  1. When starting Filesystem Imports, you are asked to select a host.
     You should see the name of the Amiga computer where you created
     the `FirstExport'. This can be a different or the same one you are
     using right now. Local imports are possible.

  2. Once you have selected the host name, you are asked to log in
     unless you use the `NOSECURITY' tooltype. As `FirstExport' has not
     been configured to require security, you can pretty much click on
     `Ok' and forget about the login information.

  3. The list view shows all the available exports now. If you have
     already imported one of them that is currently mounted, this is
     also shown in the list view.

  4. You should select the type of import now.

        À Temporary

          When you import something, it will be mounted immediately.
          There won't be any mount file created that can be used later
          or after a reboot. This can be used to access exports that
          you don't use a lot.

        À Permanent

          In addition to importing something now, a mount file will be
          created in the directory `DEVS:DOSDrivers' (or
          `SYS:WBStartup' as fallback) that causes an automatic remount
          of that import the next time you reset or power up your Amiga
          computer. If you always need an import, this is what you want.

        À Storage

          In addition to importing something now, a mount file will be
          created in `SYS:Storage/DOSDrivers'. The `Mount' command can
          then be used to mount this import after a reboot or reset on
          demand only. It will not be remounted automatically. This is
          handy for mounts that are used, but not always.

  5. Simple connect to `FirstExport' now by double clicking on its
     entry in the list view. It will be imported and depending on the
     mount mode, a mount file will be created in the appropriate place
     for later user.


@{B}NOTE:@{UB} You won't find the typical `Save', `Use', or `Cancel' functions
of the common prefs editors here. As the mount files that are or have
been created define the current configuration of your Amiga computer,
changes are immediate. To delete a permanent or storage mount
configuration, simply use the Shell or Workbench to delete the
corresponding mount file.


@EndNode


@Node "Printer Exports" "EnvoyManual.guide/Printer Exports"

@Next "Printer Imports"
@Prev "Filesystem Imports"
@Toc "Configuration"

@{B}Printer Exports
===============@{UB}

   To make printers available to other Amiga computers on the Envoy
network, you use Printer Exports. At allows you to set up arbitrary
number of exports with a descriptive name and optional security and
access options each.

@{B}Tutorial
--------@{UB}

   The idea of this tutorial is to create an export of an imaginary
printer on your `parallel.device' unit 1 and to point out a few
implications of some of the different options.

  1. You have to log in with admin privileges to do anything with
     Printer Exports. If you don't know how, you may want to back up to
     @{"Login Information" Link "Login Information"}.

  2. If you click on `Add...', a new printer export with a unique name
     is prepared. Note that exports covering the standard parallel,
     serial and printer outputs are always preconfigured for your
     convenience. We don't use them in this tutorial, though.

  3. A new export named `New Printer' has been created for you. Well,
     if you have created other exports before, a number may be appended
     to make the name unique.

  4. Change the name to `PARon1'. Don't forget to hit `ENTER' to cause
     the name change.

  5. In the device gadget, you should enter `parallel.device' now.
     After hitting `ENTER', you can also enter the unit number 1 of our
     imaginary printer.

  6. For this test, this is going to be a fairly public. We don't want
     to set up any security for this printer. Anyone may access it.
     Please remove the security checkmark. Note that you can't switch to
     the security option page anymore when the security checkmark is not
     set.

  7. Finally, we want to make the printer active to allow anyone else
     to import it. Just set the `Printer is active' checkmark to
     activate the printer.

  8. Now click on `Use' and anyone on the network will immediately be
     able to import your imaginary printer. Check @{"Printer Imports" Link "Printer Imports"} for
     more information. If you want this test export to survive reboots
     of this Amiga computer, you should click on `Save' instead.


@{B}Gadgets
-------@{UB}

   À The list view

     You can see all the exports with their respective descriptive names
     in the list view. You can also change the names by selecting an
     export and typing in a new name for it. Don't forget to hit
     `ENTER' to cause the name change.

   À The Standard Option page

        - `Device:'

        - `Unit:'

          This is the actual Exec device and unit combination that is
          made available over the network. The client will never see
          this information. You can specify any valid Exec device name,
          including the `.device' suffix, and unit number.

        - `Timeout [s/KB]:'

          To accomodate both very slow and very fast output Exec
          devices, you can specify a timeout for writes to the output
          device. The default value is 15, which means that the spooler
          would wait up to 15 seconds for 1024 bytes (1 KB) of data to
          be successfully written.  If you have a very slow output
          device, you may have to raise this timeout value to avoid
          requesters informing you about a potential problem.

        - `Security:'

          This checkmark controls the security features. If you turn
          off all security checks, anyone can access the selected
          export. By setting it, only the users or groups of users
          listed on the Security option page may actually successfully
          import this export.  To protect you from accidentally
          exporting something that you don't want, the default setting
          for this checkmark is to enable security.

        - `Printer is active:'

          To actually make a preconfigured export visible to all
          clients, you have to set this checkmark. If it is not set,
          the printer won't be available to clients. To protect you
          from having printers available that shouldn't be, the default
          setting for this checkmark is that a new export is inactive.

   À The Security Option page

     If you want to establish access restrictions for individual users
     or groups on individual files, directories, you need to deal with
     this option page.

        - `Users and Groups'

          You specify in this list view all the users and groups who may
          access this export. This check is only done if security is not
          turned off.


@EndNode


@Node "Printer Imports" "EnvoyManual.guide/Printer Imports"

@Next "Network Printing"
@Prev "Printer Exports"
@Toc "Configuration"

@{B}Printer Imports
===============@{UB}

   Printer Imports is used to set up the configuration to import
printers that were exported on this or any other Amiga computer running
Amiga Envoy with @{"Printer Exports" Link "Printer Exports"}. Note that once you have configured
you imports as described here, you still need to use `Network Printing'
to actually activate any redirection of data to an imported printer.

@{B}NOTE:@{UB} You may want to run a client without having to bother with any
security features. If you enable the Workbench tooltype `NOSECURITY'
for Printer Imports, you won't be asked for your user name and password
on startup. Obviously this also means that you can only access exports
that are not protected by security features then.

@{B}Tutorial
--------@{UB}

   You will import the export `PARon1' that you created in
@{"Printer Exports" Link "Printer Exports"}. The idea is that you don't currently have a printer
connected locally and want all the output data to be sent to `PARon1'.

  1. When starting Printer Imports, you are asked to select a host. You
     should see the name of the Amiga computer where you created the
     `PARon1'. This can be a different or the same one you are using
     right now. Local imports are possible.

  2. Once you have selected the host name, you are asked to log in
     unless you use the `NOSECURITY' tooltype. As `PARon1' has not been
     configured to require security, you can pretty much click on `Ok'
     and forget about the login information.

  3. The list view shows all the available exports now. If any of them
     are already configured to be connected to certain local data
     source as described below, you will also see this in the list view.

  4. Select `PARon1' now by clicking on its entry in the list view
     once. We will then connect it to the appropriate local data
     source. Currently, it is listed as not connected to anything.

  5. There are a few different sources of data for your imaginary
     printer possible. You chose one of them in the cycle gadget below
     the list view. Note that each data source can be only connected to
     one import at a time. You can't have data from one source routed to
     multiple imports at once.

        À Not connected

          To intentionally break a connection to a certain data source,
          you can use this option. Don't select this for `PARon1' in
          this tutorial.

        À Connect to PRT:

        À Connect to PAR:

        À Connect to SER:

          You can redirect any data that is sent to one of the named DOS
          devices. If this is configuration is set and activated, any
          data written to these devices will be sent over the network
          to the given import. Don't select this for `PARon1' in this
          tutorial.

        À Default Printer Output

          If you select this option, any data that has been processed by
          `printer.device' with the current printer driver will be sent
          to your import rather than being output locally. Please
          select this option now for the tutorial.

  6. Now click on `Use' and you will immediately be able to redirect
     data to your imaginary printer. Check @{"Network Printing" Link "Network Printing"} for more
     information. If you want this test import to survive reboots of
     this Amiga computer, you should click on `Save' instead.


@{B}NOTE:@{UB} After the configuration is set and saved as needed, you still
have to use @{"Network Printing" Link "Network Printing"} to actually activate or deactivate data
redirection.


@EndNode


@Node "Network Printing" "EnvoyManual.guide/Network Printing"

@Next "Shell Tools"
@Prev "Printer Imports"
@Toc "Configuration"

@{B}Network Printing
================@{UB}

   With Network Printing, you can enable or disable output data
redirection to configured printer imports. Obviously, the corresponding
imports need to be set up already with @{"Printer Imports" Link "Printer Imports"}. For the DOS
devices `PAR:' and `SER:', you can also specify timeout values now to
keep writes from locking up in case of hardware problems.

@{B}Tutorial
--------@{UB}

   You will enable data redirection to the imaginary printer imported
as described in @{"Printer Imports" Link "Printer Imports"}. You will also see what happens if a
print does not succeed.

  1. Start Network Printing. You don't have to deal with a login
     requester here.

  2. Note that you can enable and disable redirection of output data
     for the four data sources by setting or clearing the given
     checkmark.

  3. Via @{"Printer Imports" Link "Printer Imports"}, we have connected the default printer output
     to our imaginary `PARon1' printer. Turn on redirection now by
     setting the checkmark for `Printer Output'.

  4. Now click on `Use' and you will immediately be able to use the
     redirection. If you want this test redirection to survive reboots
     of this Amiga computer, you should click on `Save' instead.

  5. Test the redirection by using, e.g., `echo test >prt:' in a Shell.
     Data will be written to the DOS device `PRT:'.  This data will be
     sent to `printer.device', which processes it according to the
     current printer driver. The output will be redirected via Amiga
     Envoy to your imaginary `PARon1' printer, which is @{B}not@{UB} actually
     available.

  6. At first, the echo command succeeds without any problem. The data
     is sent to the Envoy Print Spooler on the server which tries to
     write it to `parallel.device' unit 1 as was configured for
     `PARon1'.

  7. After a while, the Amiga Envoy print spooler will put up a
     requester that the pritner doesn't accept the data. Well, as there
     is no printer, this message is what we expect. We can now retry or
     cancel the job.

  8. That's it, you successfully redirected some data over the print
     spooler. By adapting the configuration you can now set up your
     real printer the same way.


   While redirection data is fairly simply be setting the checkmarks,
the timeout gadgets require some more explanation. Without Amiga Envoy,
any write to `PAR:' (or `SER:' with handshaking) must succeed or it
will never finish. If you copy something to `PAR:' on the standard OS
and there is nothing hooked up to the parallel port, the process will
hang until the next reboot.

   Amiga Envoy allows you to configure timeout settings here. If you
configure any non null value for the timeouts, any write to `PAR:' or
`SER:', redirected or not, will be checked. The timeout unit is
[seconds/1024 bytes]. If the data is not accepted within the timeout, a
requester will appear. You are then given the choice to wait even
longer or to abort the request. This is similar to the requester that
`printer.device' would show in case of trouble.


@EndNode


@Node "Shell Tools" "EnvoyManual.guide/Shell Tools"

@Prev "Network Printing"
@Toc "Configuration"

@{B}Shell Tools
===========@{UB}

   For the experienced power user, Amiga Envoy also offers several
command line tools to support security features, maintenance, and
diagnostics.


 @{" Owner " Link "CLI_OwnerGroup"}            Set file/directory owner
 @{" Group " Link "CLI_OwnerGroup"}            Set file/directory group
 @{" ChangeEFSLogin " Link "CLI_ChangeEFSLogin"}   Modify login setting of an import
 @{" List " Link "CLI_List"}             (V42) Supports Amiga Envoy
 @{" Protect " Link "CLI_Protect"}          (V42) Supports Amiga Envoy
 @{" SpoolMgr " Link "CLI_SpoolMgr"}         Control Envoy print spooler


@EndNode


@Node "CLI_OwnerGroup" "EnvoyManual.guide/CLI_OwnerGroup"

@Next "CLI_ChangeEFSLogin"
@Prev "Shell Tools"
@Toc "Shell Tools"

@{B}Owner & Group
-------------@{UB}

   These Shell command tools can be used to modify the user or group ID
set for specific files or directories. Rather than specifying numeric
ID's you can simply specify the user or group name.

   À FILE/A

     This is the file or directory name or pattern for the new ID to be
     set.

   À OWNER/A (Owner tool only)

   À GROUP/A (Group tool only)

     Here, you specify the name of the user or group respectively that
     is to be set.

   À ALL/S

     To process a whole directory tree including all subdirectories, you
     can specify this option.

   À QUIET/S

     If you don't want messages printed by the tool, this option comes
     in handy.


@EndNode


@Node "CLI_ChangeEFSLogin" "EnvoyManual.guide/CLI_ChangeEFSLogin"

@Next "CLI_List"
@Prev "CLI_OwnerGroup"
@Toc "Shell Tools"

@{B}ChangeEFSLogin
--------------@{UB}

   Whenever you mount a filesystem import, the user name and password
are used that you had specified when creating the import mountfile with
Filesystem Imports. See @{"Filesystem Imports" Link "Filesystem Imports"} for more information on
creating imports.

   Sometimes you may want to change the given user name and password
for a currently mounted import to, e.g., access security protected
files under a different user ID. Normally, you probably won't use this.

   You can try to change the current login information with
`ChangeEFSLogin'. Just specify the following options as needed on th
ecommand line.

   À Mount/A

     This is the DOS device name of the currently mounted import.

   À Username

   À Password

     Specify the new user name and password here.


@EndNode


@Node "CLI_List" "EnvoyManual.guide/CLI_List"

@Next "CLI_Protect"
@Prev "CLI_ChangeEFSLogin"
@Toc "Shell Tools"

@{B}List
----@{UB}

   The V42 List command is a fully compatible replacement for the
normal List command. It supports the following additional options:

   À SORT/K

     Sort the output according to the given criteria.

        - N=NAME/S

        - S=SIZE/S

        - D=DATE/S

        - RN=REVERSENAME/S

        - RS=REVERSESIZE/S

        - RD=REVERSEDATE/S

   À USERS/S

   À GROUPS/S

     Also print information about the users and groups for each file or
     directory by translating the user or group ID's with Amiga Envoy's
     help into readable names.


@EndNode


@Node "CLI_Protect" "EnvoyManual.guide/CLI_Protect"

@Next "CLI_SpoolMgr"
@Prev "CLI_List"
@Toc "Shell Tools"

@{B}Protect
-------@{UB}

   The V42 Protect command is a fully compatible replacement for the
normal Protect command. It supports the following additional options:

   À FLAGS=USERFLAGS

     Set or clear access permission bits for the owner. This is fully
     compatible to previous usage of the Protect command.

   À GROUPFLAGS

   À OTHERFLAGS

     Set or clear access permission bits for the group or others listed.
     You can specify any combination of `rwed' here.


@EndNode


@Node "CLI_SpoolMgr" "EnvoyManual.guide/CLI_SpoolMgr"

@Prev "CLI_Protect"
@Toc "Shell Tools"

@{B}SpoolMgr
--------@{UB}

   This is a little tool to peek into the current print queue of the
Amiga Envoy print spooler for specific printers.

   À HOST/K

     This is the Envoy host specification where the spooler resides.
     Without a name, the local host is used.

   À PRINTER

     You are always accessing a specific printer when looking at the
     spooler status. Specify the export name of this printer here.

   À USER/K

   À PASSWORD/K

     Specific jobs may be spooled by specific users. To see the
     respective information for the given printer, specify the user name
     and password here as needed for security option settings.

   À LISTJOBS/S

     If you want a list of all the currently spooled jobs, use this
     switch.  Note that the numeric job ID's listed are unique and may
     not be sequential. This is the default option if you just
     specified a printer name.

   À DISCARDJOB/K/N

     To delete a specific job in the spool queue, you specify the
     numeric job ID with this option. The numeric job ID's can be
     obtained using the `LISTJOBS' switch.

   À START/S

   À STOP/S

     If, e.g., you have to do some maintenance, you may want to stop the
     print queue for a specific printer temporarily. With these options
     you can stop and restart it. Note that the calls don't nest. One
     `STOP' or `START' is always enough to stop or start the print
     queue for the named printer.

   À HOLDJOB/K/N

   À RELEASEJOB/K/N

     You can put specific jobs on hold temporarily and release them into
     the print queue again. Holding a job will move it down in the queue
     before all other held up jobs. Releasing a job moves it up beyond
     all currently held up jobs. If you use these options on the
     currently printing job, they act like the `START/S' and `STOP/S'
     options.

   À LISTPRINTERS/S

     To find out about the printer names that are accessible on the
     given host, you can use this option.


@EndNode


@Node "File Sharing" "EnvoyManual.guide/File Sharing"

@Next "Printer Sharing"
@Prev "Configuration"
@Toc "Main"

@{B}Filesystem Sharing
******************@{UB}

   This chapter talks about many concepts on filesystem sharing and
ideas to give you some helpful hints on how to approach this issue.  It
is comparatively general in nature.

   To actually set up filesystem sharing quickly, you should be
familiar with the Amiga Envoy configuration preferences tools. You
should read through @{"Configuration" Link "Configuration"}, where you can also experiment with
filesystem sharing by following the tutorials there.

@{B}An Approach for the Impatient
=============================@{UB}

   If you are fairly familiar with using your Amiga and don't want to
read about general things, you can try to follow these steps.

  1. Your networking hardware and the configuration in
     @{"Network Configuration" Link "Network Configuration"} must be set up. If you haven't done that
     yet, please refer to @{"Configuration" Link "Configuration"}.

  2. Start @{"Filesystem Exports" Link "Filesystem Exports"} on the Amiga computer where you want to
     make files available.

  3. Add exports in any way that you feel like. Give them meaningful
     names, don't forget to set up security correctly or disable it.
     Otherwise you won't be able to use your exports.

  4. On the client which is supposed to access the exported filesystem,
     create corresponding mounts with @{"Filesystem Imports" Link "Filesystem Imports"}.

  5. That's all there is to it. Nothing magical or extremely complex.


@{B}Some Concepts and Ideas
=======================@{UB}

   You have skipped the approach for impatient and you want to know
more about the ideas behind filesystem sharing in Amiga Envoy now.
Amig Envoy is trying to keep things simple, so you don't see a lot of
text below. Whenever you want to put the mentioned concepts to
practical use, just refer to @{"Configuration" Link "Configuration"}.

   Filesystem sharing in Amiga Envoy means that you are able to access
files and directories on another Amiga Envoy based Amiga computer as if
they were on your local harddrive or floppy disk. All the features of
the Amiga filesystem are supported, including file notification and
removable media support.

   Obviously, you may not always want to make everything accessible to
others over the network. Some files, like your local configuration
files should probably be private. Some files, like private letters
should definitely be private and not accessible to others. To support
this, Amiga Envoy supports access restrictions per file or directory.

   Reasons for filesystem sharing may be that you don't want to
duplicate information on many Amiga computers if you can make it
accessible on just one. Another reason may be that you have a central
backup system installed on just one Amiga computer. Yet another reason
for file sharing may be that you have just one CD-ROM drive, LS-120
drive, ZIP drive, or special Amiga HD floppy disk drive that you want
to make accessible to other Amiga computers.


@EndNode


@Node "Printer Sharing" "EnvoyManual.guide/Printer Sharing"

@Next "Troubleshooting"
@Prev "File Sharing"
@Toc "Main"

@{B}Printer Sharing
***************@{UB}

   This chapter talks about many concepts on printer sharing and ideas
to give you some helpful hints on how to approach this issue.  It is
comparatively general in nature.

   To actually set up printer sharing quickly, you should be familiar
with the Amiga Envoy configuration preferences tools. You should read
through @{"Configuration" Link "Configuration"}, where you can also experiment with printer
sharing by following the tutorials there.

@{B}An Approach for the Impatient
=============================@{UB}

   If you are fairly familiar with using your Amiga and don't want to
read about general things, you can try to follow these steps.

  1. Your networking hardware and the configuration in
     @{"Network Configuration" Link "Network Configuration"} must be set up. If you haven't done that
     yet, please refer to @{"Configuration" Link "Configuration"}.

  2. Start @{"Printer Exports" Link "Printer Exports"} on the Amiga computer where you want to make
     files available.

  3. Add exports in any way that you feel like. Give them meaningful
     names, don't forget to set up security correctly or disable it.
     Otherwise you won't be able to use your exports.

  4. On the client which is supposed to access the exported printer,
     create a corresponding configuration with @{"Printer Imports" Link "Printer Imports"}.

  5. Finally, use @{"Network Printing" Link "Network Printing"}, whenever you want to activate or
     deactivate printer sharing according to the previously set up
     configuration data.

  6. That's all there is to it. Nothing magical or extremely complex.


@{B}Some Concepts and Ideas
=======================@{UB}

   The printer system of AmigaOS is not really that great. This means
that printer sharing, or better printer data redirection, is somewhat
complex in comparison to filesystem sharing.

   Amiga Envoy allows you to redirect output data generated by
`printer.device', the AmigaOS printer support, to an output device on
on another Amiga computer. You can also optionally redirect any data
written to either one of the DOS devices `PRT:', `PAR:', or `SER:'.

   Note well that data generated by `printer.device' locally is really
output data in the format generated by the currently selected printer
driver. You have to set the correct printer driver on your local Amiga
computer to have data printed correctly on the remote Amiga computer.
You local Amiga computer does all the print processing.

   Data sent to `PRT:' would normally be sent to `printer.device' and
is therefore not yet in a printer specific output format. It uses the
data format expected by `printer.device'. Simply redirecting `PRT:' to
a printer directly may not yield the results that you expect. You can,
e.g., redirect that data to `printer.device' on the server, though.

   The @{"Printer Exports" Link "Printer Exports"} tool offers a few preconfigured settings to
route data to a specific destination on the server for your convenience.

   À PAR

     Data sent to this export printer will be written to
     `parallel.device' unit 0.

   À SER

     Data sent to this export printer will be written to
     `serial.device' unit 0.

   À PRT

     Data sent to this export printer will be written to
     `printer.device' unit 0. This means it works like the normal
     `PRT:' DOS device.

   À PRT RAW

     Data sent to this export printer will be written to
     `printer.device' unit 0, but uses the `PRD_RAWWRITE' command to
     bypass the printer driver. This means that `printer.device' on the
     server will still send the data to the configured printer out
     there, but it will not touch it in any way.  This setting can't be
     deleted.

   To actually use printer sharing or printer data redirection, check
the tutorials in @{"Configuration" Link "Configuration"} for details.


@EndNode


@Node "Troubleshooting" "EnvoyManual.guide/Troubleshooting"

@Next "Advanced Topics"
@Prev "Printer Sharing"
@Toc "Main"

@{B}Troubleshooting
***************@{UB}

   The first rule of trouble shooting: If it worked before, you must
have changed something. Find that something and fix it.

   The second rule (valid on the Amiga only): If something can't be
found or accessed, the SnoopDOS tool from Aminet often gives valuable
hints of which file or directory can't be handled correctly and why.


 @{" TCP and Amiga Envoy " Link "TCP and Amiga Envoy"}          Using both TCP/IP and Envoy
 @{" Can't see a Host " Link "Can't see a Host"}             The other computers are not accessible


@EndNode


@Node "Can't see a Host" "EnvoyManual.guide/Can't see a Host"

@Toc "Troubleshooting"

@{B}Can't see a Host
================@{UB}

   First make sure that the needed services are actually activated on
each Amiga computer. If you, e.g., don't have the `filesystem.service'
active, you can't see it when trying to access exports on that Amiga
computer, even though they may be configured correctly.

   If you have moved the Envoy installation on disk, remove and readd
the service files in Service Configuration. You want to be sure that
the services are found correctly.

   Never forget to check the actual cabling. Especially the 10Base2
connectors using Coax cable are a never ending story with bad chapters.

   Does the computer see itself, assuming the respective services are
active? If not, check your SANA device setup. Some bad SANA device may
block `nipc.library' from working correctly. If it works well, an Amiga
computer is always able to see at least itself in a simple network.

   If you use Realms, make sure the Realm server is up and running.
This is complex stuff, so don't forget to check your routing.  Without
access to its Realm server, an Amiga computer using Realms won't be
able to see any Amiga computer, not even itself.


@EndNode


@Node "Advanced Topics" "EnvoyManual.guide/Advanced Topics"

@Next "(dir)"
@Prev "Troubleshooting"
@Toc "Main"

@{B}Advanced Topics
***************@{UB}

   This chapter contains some documentation about advanced and
sometimes magical features of Amiga Envoy. If you are not yet familiar
with your Amiga Envoy installation, you may want to be very careful
when trying things described below.


 @{" Accounts Server Sharing " Link "Accounts Server Sharing"}      Share a single Accounts Server in the net
 @{" Large Spooler Files " Link "Large Spooler Files"}          If you overload the spooler
 @{" TCP and Amiga Envoy " Link "TCP and Amiga Envoy"}          Using both TCP/IP and Envoy at the same time
 @{" Magic Mount Options " Link "Magic Mount Options"}          EFS Mount features
 @{" Complex Networks and Realms " Link "Complex Networks and Realms"}  You are really getting into it!


@EndNode


@Node "Accounts Server Sharing" "EnvoyManual.guide/Accounts Server Sharing"

@Next "Large Spooler Files"
@Toc "Advanced Topics"

@{B}Accounts Server Sharing
=======================@{UB}

   Pretty much any Amiga computer running Amiga Envoy needs access to
an Accounts Server to manage and verify login information. The default
installation is that each computer runs its own Accounts Server. In
more complex setups, this means that you would have to replicate the
user and groups database for all Amiga computers. This is annyoing and
can easily lead to database management errors.

   To circumvent this, a magical feature has been added to Amiga Envoy.
If you set the environment variable `Envoy/AccountsServer' to a host
name, the Accounts Server on that host will be used rather than the
local one. By using this feature, you can use a central database for
your login information on one Amiga computer.


@EndNode


@Node "Large Spooler Files" "EnvoyManual.guide/Large Spooler Files"

@Next "TCP and Amiga Envoy"
@Prev "Accounts Server Sharing"
@Toc "Advanced Topics"

@{B}Large Spooler Files
===================@{UB}

   Normally, the Amiga Envoy Print Spooler will put all printer data
into spool files within the temporary directory `T:'. If `T:' points to
you RAM disk and someone prints an extremely large file, you may run
out of memory on the server. You have two options:

  1. Move the `T:' Assign to a hard disk with enough free space. This
     works, but it also moves everything else created in the temporary
     directory to the harddisk. You may not want that.

  2. Set a new logical Assign `ENVOYSPOOLDIR:' in your `User-Startup'
     file. If this assign is set, the spooler will put all its spool
     files in that directory instead of `T:'.



@EndNode


@Node "TCP and Amiga Envoy" "EnvoyManual.guide/TCP and Amiga Envoy"

@Next "Magic Mount Options"
@Prev "Large Spooler Files"
@Toc "Advanced Topics"

@{B}TCP and Amiga Envoy
===================@{UB}

   There are several TCP/IP protocol stacks in existence for the Amiga.
At this point of time, Amiga Envoy does not have TCP support on its
feature list. Nevertheless, it is possible to run both a TCP/IP stack
and Amiga Envoy on the same network.

   The basic issue here is that both a TCP/IP implementation and Amiga
Envoy are IP based protocol stacks that are written according to the
established standards, using both the same identification numbers for
packets. They send and receive packets via SANA-II devices. SANA-II
devices that were not written according to Release 2 of the SANA
standard will only give a packet with a certain identification to a
single protocol stack. This means that with this type of device, one of
the protocol stacks loses always. In that case, the first step would be
to update the SANA-II device.  That is a good idea in general, but
doesn't really help in this case as described below.

   The SANA-II Release 2 networking standard allows multiple protocol
stacks to use the same networking hardware. Unfortunately though, you
can't run multiple standard compliant IP implementations on the same
hardware unless you separate the packets each implementation generates.

   To understand what happens, imagine a situation where data packets
are not separated. Someone sends an Amiga Envoy request to your Amiga
computer. Amiga Envoy takes this request, handles it, and sends an
answer. The IP implementation of your TCP/IP stack on the other hand
doesn't know about the protocols of Amiga Envoy. As it is standard
compliant like Amiga Envoy, it discards the request and sends a message
back to the originator that it does not know this type of protocol. The
same situation can occur if a TCP/IP request reaches your Amiga
computer. This time, Amiga Envoy would correctly tell the originator
that it doesn't know that protocol and the TCP/IP stack would handle
the request for its protocol. Again, you get confusing results. Either
way, someone loses.

   Obviously, the originating side always gets both the rejection
message and possibly a valid reply. These confusing messages could
cause problems in a standard compliant network. In effect, it may not
work at all, @{B}because@{UB} both protocol stacks obey the official standards.

   As mentioned before, there are two ways around this.

  1. A socket.library (TCP/IP interface for the Amiga) that sits on top
     of Amiga Envoy's nipc.library. This would be the best thing,
     because nipc.library is a general IP engine which can support any
     type of IP based protocol. Unfortunately, this socket.library is
     not available currently. Feel free to write it. You just have to
     copy and adapt the TCP chapter of, e.g., Comer Book 2 to get a
     basic working TCP/IP implementation.

  2. Packet separation by specifying different IP and ARP packet types
     for your TCP/IP stack and Amiga Envoy. This is easy to do, often
     helps, and that is what is described below.


   As the Amiga TCP/IP stacks tend to be tricky to configure, you want
to reconfigure Amiga Envoy on all connected computers instead. Read
@{"Network Configuration" Link "Network Configuration"} and chose IP and ARP packet types for all
Amiga Envoy hosts that do not conflict with the default values
recommended in the standards. For Ethernet, the defaults are 2048 and
2054. You would chose 2049 and 2055 for Amiga Envoy to be different.
For ARCNET, the defaults are 240 and 241. You would chose 242 and 243
for Amiga Envoy to be different. Note that you can't use Amiga Envoy
over the Internet then, because gateways often will not handle packets
with non-standard identification numbers.


@EndNode


@Node "Magic Mount Options" "EnvoyManual.guide/Magic Mount Options"

@Next "Complex Networks and Realms"
@Prev "TCP and Amiga Envoy"
@Toc "Advanced Topics"

@{B}Magic Mount Options
===================@{UB}

   This section tells you about special options to influence behaviour
of filesystem mounts and a way to kill (or dismount) imports under
certain circumstances.

@{B}Mount Behaviour
---------------@{UB}

   Whenever you create an EFS import, a mountfile is created and used.
For permanent EFS imports, you can modify certain aspects of the
filesystem's behaviour via some options. To do this, you have to edit
the permanent mountfile typically stored in either `Storage/DOSDrivers'
or `DEVS:DOSDrivers' appropriately.

Inside the mount file, this could be a default `Unit' entry:

     Unit="A600ªRAM6ªª$strangetextª"

   You can add three different characters beyond the broken vertical
bar with another broken vertical bar as final terminator to force some
special mount behaviour.

   À `B'

     Suppress access to the Workbench `.backdrop' file on the server.
     This is nice if left out icons on the server get in the way or if
     you want to protect the server's `.backdrop' file when it could
     normally be modified.

   À `D'

     This option suppresses modification of the `Disk.info' file on the
     server. In effect, it protects the disk icon on the server from
     modification by the client.

   À `R'

     Sometimes you want to have a permanent mount that may not be
     accessible at all times. You can turn off all network error
     requesters by the EFS client with this letter.

   The following example shows how the `Unit' entry needs to be
modified to protect the export's disk icon and to suppress any network
error requesters by the client.

     Unit="A600ªRAM6ªª$strangetextªDRª"

@{B}Killing an Import
-----------------@{UB}

   There is a certain functionality called `ACTION_DIE' to shut down
file systems on the Amiga. Unfortunately it can never work safely in
the general case due to basic design flaws in DOS. Still, it is
implemented in the EFS client to help testing. If you can make sure
that noone accesses an import at a certain time, you can use a tool to
send an `ACTION_DIE' to the import's handler to shut down that import
completely. Again, in the general case this is @{B}not@{UB} safe and could
possibly crash your Amiga computer.  Sometimes, it is handy
nevertheless. Use this at your own risk.


@EndNode


@Node "Complex Networks and Realms" "EnvoyManual.guide/Complex Networks and Realms"

@Prev "Magic Mount Options"
@Toc "Advanced Topics"

@{B}Complex Networks and Realms
===========================@{UB}

   This is so complex that the documentation doesn't even really exist
yet! Many things can easily be configured wrong here and we haven't
figured out a way to support this really well, so we don't support it.
Use this functionality at your own risk. If it works, fine. If it
doesn't work, sorry. Maybe in the next release.

   Basically, complex networking is about two things. First, you don't
have all the Amiga Envoy based Amiga computers hooked to the same
networking cable. Second, in any such situation, you must use Realms
and a Realm server.

   Before reading on, you should make sure that you are very firm on
the concepts and ideas outlined in @{"Beginner's Info" Link "Beginner's Info"}.  Especially
knowledge on IP addresses, net masks, and subnetting should be part of
your life.

@{B}Realms and Realm Servers
------------------------@{UB}

   Realms are a way to group the Amiga computers on your network
according to their functions by naming those groups. Say that you have
an accounting department in your company with two Amigas named
`Asterix' and `Obelix'. You also have an engineering department with
two Amigas named `Intrepid' and `Defiant'.

   You could hook all of them onto the same cable and whenever anyone
tries to import a file or printer, she may be able to see all four
Amigas while selecting a host name. Whenever a host requester opens
with Amiga Envoy without Realms being set up, all the Amiga computers
on the same cable that can be accessed will be listed.

   On the other hand, you want make sure that normally your accountants
only see the Amiga computers for the accounting department and that
normally the engineers only see those in the engineering department. So
you set up two Realms via `Network Configuration', one named `Beans'
for accounting and one named `Screws' for engineering.

   Each Realm needs at least one Amiga computer that acts as Realm
Server. This computer is normally actively part of that realm but
really doesn't have to be. It is also possible to set up a Realm Server
that isn't used for anything else.

   Let's assume that we decided to use `Beans:Obelix' and
`Screws:Defiant' as Realm Server for the respective Realms.  You may
have noticed the notation with a colon in the previous sentence. With
@{"Network Configuration" Link "Network Configuration"} you enable usage of a Realm Server for all the
four Amigas and enter the respective Realm name and the IP addresses of
the server Amiga computers for that Realm. On the two servers, you also
have to configure that this host is a Realm Server.

   Now that the Realm members are configured to access the respective
Realm Servers, we have to configure the Realm Servers. When you have
turned on the Realm Server functinonality in @{"Network Configuration" Link "Network Configuration"}, you
can access a `Realm Configuration' panel.

   In that panel, you enter information for local Realms and remote
Realms. Into the list view for local Realms, you can enter Realm names
and network or host addresses for the Realms that this Realm Server is
supposed to handle. If you have a complex network where some Amiga
computers are located in a different subnet, you can add Realm names
and IP addresses for the Realm Servers serving that remote subnet into
the remote Realms list view.

@{B}Gateways
--------@{UB}

   Are you sure you want to get into this? Really? Amiga Envoy should
be able to handle this, but it's a very complex topic.  Again, we
haven't figured out well how to support it, so use it at your own risk.
If it works, fine. If it doesn't work, sorry.  Maybe in the next
release.

   Basically any Amiga computer running Amiga Envoy must act as gateway
which sits in between different subnets and should pass on packets from
one connection (e.g., Ethernet) to another connection (e.g., ARCNET).
If the computer is not configured to be a gateway, it will not
automatically forward data packets and discard any packets that it
doesn't handle itself. Turning on gateway functionality only makes
sense if you have more than one physical network connection for one
Amiga computer. You should know what your are doing. Studying RFC's or
books about IP based networks should help.

   If you have a default gateway on a cable, you should configure all
the hosts on that cable to send unknown information to that default
gateway.

@EndNode

